\f0\b\fs40 \cf0 Directions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa140\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs38 \cf0 Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F.\
For the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/caramel/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 caramel}}, heat 1 1/2 cups of the sugar and 1/2 cup water in a small, heavy-bottomed saucepan until the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/sugar/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 sugar}} dissolves. Cook over medium heat until the syrup turns a warm caramel color. Don't stir, just swirl it in the pan. Off the heat, add 1/2 cup water and 1/2 teaspoon of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/vanilla/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 vanilla}}; be careful, the syrup will bubble violently. Stir and cook over high heat until the caramel reaches 230 degrees F ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/thread-stage/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 thread stage}}) on a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/candy/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 candy}} thermometer. Set aside.\
For the praline, combine the almonds with 1/4 cup of the caramel and spread them on a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/sheet-pan/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 sheet pan}} lined with parchment paper. Bake for 10 to 12 minutes, until the almonds are lightly browned. Allow to cool at room temperature and then break up in pieces.\
Lower the oven to 250 degrees F. Line 2 sheet pans with parchment paper.\
For the meringues, beat the egg whites, salt, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cream-of-tartar/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cream of tartar}} in the bowl of an electric mixer fitted with the whisk attachment on medium speed until {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/frothy/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 frothy}}. Turn the mixer on high speed and add the remaining 1 cup of sugar. Beat until the egg whites are very stiff and glossy. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/whisk/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Whisk}} in the remaining teaspoon of vanilla. With dessert spoons place 12 mounds of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/meringue/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 meringue}} on the parchment paper and bake for 20 minutes, or until a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cake/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cake}} tester comes out clean.\
For serving, pour creme anglaise on the bottom of individual plates. Place a meringue on top of each serving, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/drizzle/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 drizzle}} with caramel sauce, sprinkle with praline, and serve.\
To make a day or two ahead, leave the caramel and praline at room temperature\
and refrigerate the creme anglaise. Bake the meringues before guests arrive and assemble the desserts just before serving.\
