\f1\b0\fs38 \cf0 Creme Anglaise:\
4 extra-large egg yolks\
1/2 cup sugar\
1 teaspoon cornstarch\
1 3/4 cups scalded {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/milk/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 milk}}\
1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract\
1 1/2 teaspoons {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cognac/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Cognac}}\
Seeds of 1/2 vanilla bean, optional\
Beat the egg yolks and sugar in the bowl of an electric {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/mixer/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 mixer}} fitted with the paddle attachment on medium-high speed for 3 minutes, or until very thick. Reduce to low speed, and add the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cornstarch/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cornstarch}}.\
With the mixer still on low, slowly pour the hot milk into the eggs. Pour the custard mixture into a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/saucepan/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 saucepan}} and cook over low heat, stirring constantly with a wooden spoon, until thickened. The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/custard/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 custard}} will coat the spoon like heavy cream. Don't cook it above 180 degrees F or the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/eggs/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 eggs}} will scramble!\
Pour the sauce through a fine {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/strainer/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 strainer}}, add the vanilla extract, Cognac, and vanilla seeds, if using, and chill.\
Yield: 2 cups\
